Automatic Ticket Classification

Create a model to automatically classify customer complaints based on the products and services mentioned in the support tickets. By automating the classification process, the financial company can route the tickets to the correct department, improving efficiency and customer satisfaction.

Problem Statement¶

Customer complaints are crucial for financial companies, as they highlight shortcomings in products or services. Addressing these complaints quickly and effectively reduces customer dissatisfaction and enhances loyalty. Moreover, analyzing these complaints helps the company identify areas for service improvement.

However, customer complaints are typically unstructured text data. As the company grows, manually categorizing each support ticket to the relevant department becomes increasingly cumbersome. This case study will involve automating this process using NLP techniques to improve the company's ticket classification system.

In this project, you will be working as an NLP engineer for a financial company offering products such as credit cards, bank accounts, and mortgages. The objective is to develop a system that classifies customer complaints into categories based on the products and services mentioned.

Business Goal¶

Your goal is to build a model that can automatically classify customer complaints into relevant categories. This will help route the complaints to the appropriate department, allowing for faster resolution of issues and improved customer satisfaction.

The solution will involve Non-Negative Matrix Factorization (NMF) for topic modeling, which will help identify patterns and recurring words in the tickets. These patterns will allow you to cluster tickets into relevant categories.

The five categories for classification are:

  1. Credit card / Prepaid card
  2. Bank account services
  3. Theft/Dispute reporting
  4. Mortgages/Loans
  5. Others

After clustering the complaints using NMF, you will be able to use this information to train a supervised model (e.g., logistic regression, decision tree, random forest) to automatically classify new complaints into the correct department.

Steps to be Followed¶

To complete this assignment, follow the eight major tasks outlined below:

1. Data Loading¶

  • Load the .json data containing customer complaints provided by the company.
  • Ensure the data is correctly parsed and formatted for further processing.

2. Text Preprocessing¶

  • Clean the text data by removing irrelevant characters, stopwords, and applying techniques such as stemming or lemmatization.
  • Ensure the text is in a consistent format for the next stages.

3. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • Perform an initial analysis of the text data to understand the distribution of complaints.
  • Visualize the data to explore patterns, common words, and potential topics.
  • Identify any missing values or issues that need addressing in the dataset.

4. Feature Extraction¶

  • Convert the cleaned text into numerical features using techniques like TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) or Count Vectorization.
  • This step prepares the data for topic modeling and classification.

5. Topic Modelling¶

  • Apply Non-Negative Matrix Factorization (NMF) to uncover latent topics from the text data.
  • Analyze the topics to understand the common themes and categorize customer complaints into relevant groups.
  • Use the resulting topic clusters to group the tickets into the five predefined categories.

6. Model Building Using Supervised Learning¶

  • Based on the topic modeling results, build a classification model to predict the appropriate department for each customer complaint.
  • Choose from algorithms like Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, or Random Forest for model building.

7. Model Training and Evaluation¶

  • Split the dataset into training and testing sets.
  • Train the model using the training set and evaluate its performance on the testing set using metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score.

8. Model Inference¶

  • Once the model is trained and evaluated, use it to classify new customer complaint tickets automatically.
  • Test the model's ability to generalize to unseen data and ensure its practical applicability in real-world scenarios.

Conclusion¶

By following these steps, you will develop a robust system for automatically classifying customer complaints based on their content. This solution will streamline the customer support process and allow the company to address customer issues more effectively and efficiently.

def calculate_nulls(df):
    """
    Calculate the number of null values and their percentage for each column in the DataFrame.
    
    Parameters:
    df (pandas.DataFrame): The input DataFrame to analyze.
    
    Returns:
    pandas.DataFrame: A DataFrame with the count and percentage of null values for each column.
    """
    # Calculate the number of null values for each column
    null_count = df.isnull().sum()

    # Calculate the percentage of null values for each column
    null_percentage = (df.isnull().sum() / len(df)) * 100

    # Combine both into a DataFrame for easier viewing
    null_info = pd.DataFrame({'Null Count': null_count, 'Null Percentage': null_percentage})

    # Return the result
    return null_info

# Text Cleaning Function
def clean_text(text):
    # Lowercasing
    text = text.lower()  
    
    # Remove text in square brackets
    text = re.sub(r'\[.*?\]', '', text)  
    
    # Remove words containing numbers
    text = re.sub(r'\w*\d\w*', '', text)  
   
    # Remove specific word 'xxxx xxxx / xxxx / xx'
    text = re.sub(r'x+', '', text)
    
    # Remove punctuation
    text = text.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))  
    
    # Tokenize the text
    words = word_tokenize(text)
    
    # Remove stopwords
    words = [word for word in words if word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    
    return ' '.join(words)

# Lemmatization Function
def lemmatize_text(text):
    # Initialize the lemmatizer
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    
    # Tokenize the text again after cleaning
    words = word_tokenize(text)
    
    # Lemmatize each word (considering the word as a verb)
    words = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v') for word in words]
    
    return ' '.join(words)

# Function to extract POS tags NN (Nouns)
def extract_noun_phrases(text):
    # Process the text using spaCy's NLP pipeline
    doc = nlp(text)
    
    # Extract tokens with POS tag 'NN' (singular noun)
    nouns = [token.text for token in doc if token.pos_ == 'NOUN']
    
    # Join the nouns into a single string and return
    return ' '.join(nouns)

Finding the Top Unigrams, Bigrams and Trigrams :

Identify the most frequent unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams from all the complaints after processing the text.

In [19]:
def get_top_n_ngrams(text, ngram=1, top=30):
    """
    Function to extract the top n unigrams, bigrams, or trigrams based on frequency from the text data.
    
    Parameters:
    text (list): A list of text documents (e.g., complaint descriptions).
    ngram (int): The size of the n-gram (1 for unigram, 2 for bigram, 3 for trigram).
    top (int): The number of top n-grams to return.
    
    Returns:
    list: A list of tuples containing n-grams and their frequency.
    """
    # Initialize CountVectorizer with the specified ngram range and stop words
    vec = CountVectorizer(ngram_range=(ngram, ngram), stop_words='english').fit(text)
    
    # Create a bag-of-words model
    bag_of_words = vec.transform(text)
    
    # Sum the word frequencies across all documents (rows)
    sum_words = bag_of_words.sum(axis=0)
    
    # Get the vocabulary and their respective frequencies
    words_freq = [(word, sum_words[0, idx]) for word, idx in vec.vocabulary_.items()]
    
    # Sort the words by frequency in descending order
    words_freq = sorted(words_freq, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    
    # Return the top n words based on frequency
    return words_freq[:top]

def plot_top_ngrams(ngrams, title):
    """
    Function to plot the top n-grams with their frequencies in a bar chart.
    
    Parameters:
    ngrams (list): A list of tuples containing n-grams and their frequency.
    title (str): The title of the plot.
    """
    # Convert the top ngrams data into a DataFrame
    df = pd.DataFrame(ngrams, columns=['ngram', 'count'])
    
    # Plot the top n-grams as a bar chart
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    fig = sns.barplot(x=df['ngram'], y=df['count'], palette='viridis')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16)
    plt.xlabel('N-grams', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=12)
    plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to avoid clipping
    plt.show()

# Function to plot ROC curve (updated for multiclass classification)
def plot_roc_curve(model_name, y_train, y_test, train_preds_prob, test_preds_prob, n_classes):
    # Binarize the outputs for multiclass
    y_train_bin = label_binarize(y_train, classes=[i for i in range(n_classes)])
    y_test_bin = label_binarize(y_test, classes=[i for i in range(n_classes)])

    # Prepare the ROC curve for each class
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

    # ROC curve for each class
    for i in range(n_classes):
        fpr_train, tpr_train, _ = roc_curve(y_train_bin[:, i], train_preds_prob[:, i])
        fpr_test, tpr_test, _ = roc_curve(y_test_bin[:, i], test_preds_prob[:, i])

        roc_auc_train = auc(fpr_train, tpr_train)
        roc_auc_test = auc(fpr_test, tpr_test)

        # Plot ROC curve for train and test
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.plot(fpr_train, tpr_train, lw=2, label=f'Class {i} Train ROC (area = {roc_auc_train:.2f})')
        
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.plot(fpr_test, tpr_test, lw=2, label=f'Class {i} Test ROC (area = {roc_auc_test:.2f})')

    # Add some plot details
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='gray', linestyle='--', lw=2)
    plt.title(f'ROC Curve - {model_name} (Train)')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.legend(loc='lower right')

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='gray', linestyle='--', lw=2)
    plt.title(f'ROC Curve - {model_name} (Test)')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.legend(loc='lower right')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Function to plot confusion matrix
def plot_confusion_matrix(model_name, y_train, y_test, train_preds, test_preds):
    # Confusion matrix for train and test sets
    cm_train = confusion_matrix(y_train, train_preds)
    cm_test = confusion_matrix(y_test, test_preds)

    # Plot confusion matrix for train set
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.heatmap(cm_train, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False, xticklabels=['Class 0', 'Class 1'], yticklabels=['Class 0', 'Class 1'])
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix - {model_name} (Train)')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('True')

    # Plot confusion matrix for test set
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.heatmap(cm_test, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False, xticklabels=['Class 0', 'Class 1'], yticklabels=['Class 0', 'Class 1'])
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix - {model_name} (Test)')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('True')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Initialize the classifiers (as before)
mnb = MultinomialNB()
log_reg = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)
dtc = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=40)
rfc = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=40, n_jobs=-1, oob_score=True)

# Hyperparameters for each classifier (as before)
mnb_params = { 'alpha': [1, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001] }
log_params = { 'C': [0.01, 1, 10], 'penalty': ['l1', 'l2'], 'solver': ['liblinear', 'newton-cg', 'saga'] }
dtc_params = { 'max_depth': [20, 30], 'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10] }
rfc_params = { 'max_depth': [20, 30], 'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10], 'n_estimators': [100, 200] }

# Dictionary for model hyperparameter tuning with GridSearchCV (as before)
tuned_models = {
    "Multinomial Naive Bayes": (mnb, mnb_params),
    "Logistic Regression": (log_reg, log_params),
    "Decision Tree Classifier": (dtc, dtc_params),
    "Random Forest Classifier": (rfc, rfc_params)
}

# Dictionary to store grid search results
grid_search_results = {}

# DataFrame to store metrics
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Model", "Train Accuracy", "Test Accuracy"])

# Loop through each model and perform GridSearchCV
for model_name, (model, params) in tuned_models.items():
    print("-"*50)
    print(f"________ {model_name} ________")
    print("-"*50)
    print(f"Performing GridSearchCV for {model_name}...")
    
    # Initialize GridSearchCV with 5-fold cross-validation
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=params, cv=5, n_jobs=-1, verbose=1)
    
    # Fit the model to the training data
    grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Store the results in the dictionary
    grid_search_results[model_name] = grid_search

    # Display the best parameters and best score from cross-validation
    print(f"Best parameters for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_params_}")
    print(f"Best cross-validation score for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_score_}\n")
    
    # Get the best model from GridSearchCV
    best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
    best_model

    # Predict on the training data and calculate accuracy
    train_preds = best_model.predict(X_train)
    train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, train_preds)
    
    # Predict on the test data and calculate accuracy
    test_preds = best_model.predict(X_test)
    test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, test_preds)
    
    # Get probabilities for ROC curve (multiclass)
    train_preds_prob = best_model.predict_proba(X_train)
    test_preds_prob = best_model.predict_proba(X_test)
    
    # Print classification report
    print_classification_report(model_name, y_test, test_preds)
    
    # Save the model
    save_model(best_model, model_name)
    
    # Append the results to the DataFrame using pd.concat
    metrics_df = pd.concat([metrics_df, pd.DataFrame([{
        "Model": model_name,
        "Train Accuracy": train_accuracy,
        "Test Accuracy": test_accuracy
    }])], ignore_index=True)
    
    print(f"Training accuracy for {model_name}: {train_accuracy:.4f}")
    print(f"Test accuracy for {model_name}: {test_accuracy:.4f}\n")
    
    # Plot ROC Curve
    plot_roc_curve(model_name, y_train, y_test, train_preds_prob, test_preds_prob, n_classes=len(set(y_train)))
    
    # Plot Confusion Matrix
    plot_confusion_matrix(model_name, y_train, y_test, train_preds, test_preds)

Conclusion 🏁📊¶

In this case study, we successfully built and evaluated several machine learning models to automate the classification of customer complaints into relevant categories for a financial company. The ultimate goal was to enhance efficiency and improve customer satisfaction by automatically routing tickets to the correct department. The results from the models provide valuable insights into their effectiveness:

  • Logistic Regression performed exceptionally well with a train accuracy of 99.97% and test accuracy of 97.57%, making it the best model for the task. 🎯
  • Decision Tree Classifier achieved a train accuracy of 91.77% and test accuracy of 83.20%, showing solid performance but slightly lower than Logistic Regression. 🌳
  • Multinomial Naive Bayes gave a train accuracy of 86.92% and test accuracy of 79.84%, indicating it’s a good option but not as accurate as the top performers. 📚
  • Random Forest Classifier reached a train accuracy of 85.69% and test accuracy of 80.71%, making it a reliable model but still lagging behind Logistic Regression. 🌲

Based on these results, Logistic Regression is the best choice for automating the classification of customer complaints, offering high accuracy and strong generalization capabilities. 📈💡

By implementing this model, the company can streamline its customer support process, improve the accuracy of complaint routing, and ultimately boost customer satisfaction. 🎉👏

Next Steps:¶

  • Further fine-tuning of the Logistic Regression model could be explored to improve its performance even more.
  • Real-time integration of the model into the company’s ticketing system will be crucial for immediate impact. 🔧🚀
